            "type": "card",
            "title": "VH-VL Interface Architecture",
            "color": "blue",
            "content": "The VH-VL interface is a non-covalent domain-domain interaction that stabilises the Fv (variable fragment) and positions the six CDR loops for antigen recognition. Unlike the CH1-CL interface, which is reinforced by an inter-chain disulfide bond (C220-C214 in IgG1), the VH-VL interaction relies entirely on hydrophobic packing and hydrogen bonds. The interface buries approximately 700 Å² of solvent-accessible surface area per domain (~1400 Å² total), which is relatively modest for a protein-protein interaction. This buried surface area consists primarily of hydrophobic residues from the inner faces of each β-sandwich, supplemented by 2-4 hydrogen bonds at the periphery. The interface is formed by residues from framework regions FR2 and FR4 of both VH and VL, plus contributions from the base of certain CDR loops (particularly HCDR3 and LCDR3). The modest size of this interface is functionally significant: it provides sufficient stability for antigen binding while allowing the conformational flexibility needed for induced-fit binding. However, it also means the VH-VL association is the weakest domain-domain interaction in the intact IgG, making it the primary vulnerability in engineered formats (scFv, diabody) that lack the CH1-CL stabilising scaffold."
