            "content": "The Vernier zone was defined by Foote and Winter (J. Mol. Biol. 1992) as the set of framework residues that support CDR loop conformations without directly contacting antigen. These residues form the \"platform\" on which the CDR loops are displayed and are named by analogy with the vernier scale on a caliper — they make fine adjustments to CDR loop positioning. Vernier zone residues in VH (Kabat numbering): 2, 4, 27, 28, 29, 30, 36, 47, 48, 49, 67, 69, 71, 73, 78, 93, 94. Vernier zone residues in VL (Kabat numbering): 2, 4, 35, 36, 46, 47, 48, 49, 64, 66, 68, 69, 71, 98. During CDR grafting (humanisation), if the human acceptor framework has different residues at Vernier positions compared to the donor (mouse, rabbit, etc.), the CDR loops may adopt incorrect conformations, leading to loss of binding affinity. The standard rescue strategy is to \"back-mutate\" critical Vernier residues from the human acceptor sequence to the parental donor sequence. This is the single most important step in humanisation troubleshooting and accounts for 60-80% of successful humanisation rescues."
