            "color": "amber",
            "content": "The sole covalent linkage between the heavy-chain constant region and the light chain is the inter-chain disulfide bond between C220 (CH1, EU numbering) and C214 (CL, EU numbering). In IgG1, this bond forms post-translationally in the ER after chaperone-assisted folding of each domain. The C220 residue sits at the C-terminal end of the CH1 domain, while C214 is at the C-terminal end of CL. The bond geometry is solvent-exposed, making it susceptible to partial reduction under manufacturing stress. Under non-reducing CE-SDS, loss of this bond produces a characteristic ~25 kDa free light chain peak and a ~150 kDa species lacking one LC. IgG2 differs fundamentally: the inter-chain disulfide connects C131 (CH1) to C214 (CL) via a shorter linker, and IgG2 can form multiple disulfide isoforms (A, A/B, B) depending on redox conditions in the hinge-CH1 region."
