            "title": "Glycan–Lower Hinge Contacts — L234/L235 Positioning",
            "color": "amber",
            "content": "The structural connection between the N297 glycan and the lower hinge is the mechanistic basis for why glycosylation controls effector function. Crystal structures of Fc alone and Fc–FcγR complexes (PDB 3AVE, 3SGJ, 1T89) reveal that the α1,6-arm of the glycan (the arm bearing the antennary GlcNAc, galactose, and optional sialic acid) extends from the CH2 inner face toward the lower hinge, making van der Waals contacts with the backbone of residues 234–237 (the LLGG motif). These contacts position the Leu234 and Leu235 side chains in the outward-facing orientation required for insertion into the hydrophobic groove on FcγRIIIa. When the glycan is removed, the lower hinge segment becomes disordered (invisible in X-ray electron density maps), and L234/L235 can no longer engage the receptor. The α1,3-arm of the glycan (the arm bearing the other antennary GlcNAc) projects inward between the two CH2 domains and makes contacts primarily with the C’E loop of the same CH2 domain, contributing to the inter-CH2 spacing. The combination of α1,6-arm–lower hinge contacts and α1,3-arm–CH2 bracing creates the open Fc conformation essential for all FcγR interactions."
