            "type": "card",
            "title": "CDC Activity — G2F > G1F > G0F Hierarchy",
            "color": "purple",
            "content": "Complement-dependent cytotoxicity (CDC) follows the galactosylation hierarchy: G2F > G1F > G0F. The magnitude of the CDC difference is typically 2–4-fold between G2F and G0F, substantially less dramatic than the 20–50-fold ADCC enhancement from afucosylation. Hodoniczky et al. (Biotechnol. Prog., 2005) used enzymatically remodelled IgG1 glycovariants to demonstrate the systematic relationship: complete degalactosylation (G0F-only) reduced CDC to approximately 40–60% of the fully galactosylated (G2F-enriched) control, while intermediate galactosylation (G1F-dominant) showed intermediate CDC. The CDC effect is clinically relevant for rituximab-type anti-CD20 antibodies where CDC is a significant contributor to B-cell depletion, but is less relevant for most ADCC-dominant oncology mAbs. For CDC-dependent molecules, galactosylation becomes a Tier 1 CQA with specification ranges that maintain G1F + G2F above a defined threshold (typically >40–50% combined). Process control of galactosylation through Mn²⁺ supplementation, temperature shift, and UDP-galactose feed becomes critical for CDC-dependent products."
