            "content": "Galactosylation is monitored by the same glycan profiling methods used for the overall Asn297 glycan distribution. HILIC-FLD with 2-AB or 2-AA labelled released glycans provides baseline resolution of G0F, G1F(α1,3), G1F(α1,6), and G2F peaks. The galactosylation index (GI) is calculated as: GI = (0.5 × %G1F + 1.0 × %G2F) / (%G0F + %G1F + %G2F), ranging from 0 (fully agalactosylated) to 1.0 (fully galactosylated). Typical CHO IgG1 GI is 0.20–0.45. CE-LIF with APTS labelling provides rapid in-process galactosylation monitoring within 2–4 hours (versus 24–48 hours for HILIC-FLD). Intact mass spectrometry can resolve G0F, G1F, and G2F glycoforms on the intact or subunit (Fc/2) level, providing an orthogonal confirmation. For CDC-dependent products, the galactosylation specification should be correlated with C1q binding ELISA and CDC cell-based potency data. The correlation dataset should span at least 10–20 batches covering the development and clinical manufacturing history to establish the galactosylation–CDC relationship within the design space."
