            "content": "C1q is a 460 kDa soluble glycoprotein that initiates the classical complement pathway. It is composed of 18 polypeptide chains — six copies each of the A, B, and C chains — assembled into a \"bouquet of tulips\" architecture. Each A-B-C heterotrimer forms a collagen-like triple helix stalk (~75 nm) terminating in a C-terminal globular head domain (gC1q, ~47 kDa per trimer). The six stalks converge at their N-termini into a central fibrillar hub. The six gC1q heads are the IgG Fc-binding modules, each recognising a distinct Fc region. The gC1q head engages the CH2 domain face of IgG at a site centred on P329 and P331 (EU numbering), with additional contacts at D270, K322, P329, and K326. Critical requirement: a single monomeric IgG binds C1q with Ka ~10⁴ M⁻¹ — far too weak for stable engagement at physiological C1q concentrations (~70 µg/mL in serum). Activation requires at least two gC1q heads to simultaneously engage adjacent Fc regions, providing avidity (apparent Ka ~10⁷ M⁻¹). This multivalent requirement ensures that C1q activates only when IgG is clustered on a target surface."
