            "type": "card",
            "title": "Overlapping and Competing Residue Networks",
            "color": "red",
            "content": "A critical challenge in Fc engineering is that the effector function contact sites overlap and compete. The lower hinge (L234/L235) is the primary contact for all FcγRs — LALA mutations that silence ADCC also silence ADCP. The CH2–CH3 elbow (I253/H310/H435) is shared by FcRn and Protein A — some FcRn-enhancing mutations (YTE) modestly reduce Protein A binding. The CH2 body around P329/P331 is the C1q contact face, adjacent to FcγR contacts at D265/I332 — engineering one can affect the other. The N297 glycan maintains CH2 conformation required by all Fc receptors — removing it (N297A) abolishes ADCC, ADCP, and CDC simultaneously but also risks CH2 destabilisation and aggregation. Understanding this interconnected residue network is essential for predicting off-target effects of any Fc modification. Every Fc mutation should be characterised against the full panel: FcγRI, FcγRIIa (H131/R131), FcγRIIb, FcγRIIIa (V158/F158), FcγRIIIb, C1q, FcRn (pH 6.0 and 7.4), and Protein A. Omitting any receptor from the panel creates blind spots."
